Hispanics in the United States are two to three times more likely to
develop diabetes than the general population.  Heredity and diet seem
to be important factors in a disease that affects 14- 21% of Hispanics
and up to 40% of those 64 to 75 years of age, compared to 7% of all
Americans.

Heredity, a high fat diet and obesity are predisposing factors,
especially in those with American Indian ancestry.

Management includes diet, exercise and medication.

The St. Louis Health Center in Morgan Hill, California is sponsoring a
diabetes management program for Hispanic diabetics.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d56"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA101289-0194"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

One in eight Latino adults in the LA area have diabetes, a higher
incidence than in any other ethnic group except American Indians.
Nationwide estimates are that more than two million Latinos are
diabetic.  An educational effort is underway in California.

Adult onset diabetes is preventable by diet and exercise, and obesity
is a predisposing factor.  It is believed that Latino immigrants
frequently eat a fast or fatty food diet and exercise less, causing
obesity and, frequently, diabetes, according to the Diabetes
Association, which is sponsoring education programs including
information on prevention, symptoms and complications of the
disease.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d56"
TYPE="PERDOC"
