DOCREF="AP890313-0198"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

Twelve million Americans have diabetes but the incidence is highest in
minorities - Native Americans, Hispanics and blacks.  Hispanics are
three times as likely to develop diabetes as the general population;
40% of the 700,000 victims in Texas are Mexican-Americans.  San
Antonio (50% Hispanic) is the center of diabetes investigation, at the
University of Texas Health Center, which has attracted a team of
investigators from Yale.

Researchers are reaching out to the population by taking a mobile
home, equipped to test for the disease, out to city neighborhoods.

Ultimately they hope to locate a gene presidposing to the disease,
which might lead to a screening test.

They believe that poor hispanics' diet, lack of exercise and medical
care increases the risk.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d56"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890314-0237"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

San Antonio, Texas, with a 50% Hispanic population, has become a
center for the study of diabetes in Hispanics.  Dr. Ralph DeFronzo
left his diabetes research center at Yale University to relocate to
the University of Texas at San Antonio to study the local population.

His researchers are reaching out in a mobile home which roams the
neighborhoods and tests inhabitants for the disease.

Dr. DeFronzo's researchers believe that poor Hispanics' diet of cheap
processed foods, their lack of exercise and infrequent medical
attention are the root causes of their predisposition.  They believe
education of children may be critical.</SUM>
